\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 1: (34 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In problem set 2, you showed that Maxwell's equations for a time-harmonic
 current 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\vec{J}}(\vec{x})e^{-i\omega t}$
\end_inset

 yield the following linear equation for the time-harmonic fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\vec{E}}(\vec{x})e^{-i\omega t}$
\end_inset

 (with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c=1$
\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{A}\vec{E}=\left(\nabla\times\nabla\times{}-\omega^{2}\varepsilon\right)\hat{\vec{E}}=i\omega\hat{\vec{J}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon(\omega,\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 may be complex, corresponding to (linear) gain or loss.
 In a passive system, the external current 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{J}$
\end_inset

 must supply energy (do nonnegative time-averaged work), and not receive
 energy (have work done on it).
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega>0$
\end_inset

, show that this leads to a constraint on the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\Im\hat{A}=\frac{\hat{A}-\hat{A}^{\dagger}}{2i}$
\end_inset

 (which is Hermitian) being positive or negative definite or semidefinite,
 and hence leads to a constraint on 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\operatorname{Im}\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 identical to the one from class.
